	<h1>Fruits</h1>
<p>Fruits are naturally sweet and nutritious foods that come in a wide variety of colors, shapes, and flavors. They are packed with essential vitamins, minerals, and fiber that  
	help keep the body healthy. Eating fruits daily boosts the immune system and provides energy for everyday activities.
	<br> Some popular fruits include apples, bananas, mangoes, oranges, and grapes. Seasonal fruits are especially fresh and tasty, offering unique benefits during different times 
	of the year. Many fruits are rich in antioxidants, which protect the body from harmful free radicals. They can be eaten raw, juiced, or added to salads and desserts. Fruits
	 also help improve digestion and keep the skin glowing. Doctors often advise including a variety of fruits in our diet for balanced nutrition. Overall, fruits are natureâ€™s
	  gift that makes our meals healthy, colorful, and delicious.</p>
	<hr>
	<h2>Vegetables</h2>
	<p>Vegetables are healthy foods that provide our body with vitamins, minerals, and fiber. They come in many types such as leafy greens, roots, stems, and beans. Eating vegetables 
	daily helps us stay strong and prevents many diseases. Some common vegetables include carrots, potatoes, spinach, cauliflower, and tomatoes. They are usually low in fat and
	 calories, making them great for a balanced diet. Green vegetables are especially rich in iron and calcium, which are important for our bones and blood.<br> Vegetables also
	  improve digestion and keep our body refreshed. They can be cooked, boiled, fried, or even eaten raw in salads. Doctors recommend eating a variety of vegetables to stay 
	  fit and healthy. In short, vegetables are an important part of our meals and a key to good health.</p>
	
